	(63,'5 ways to manage your studying time','5-ways-manage-studying-time',NULL,NULL,'Do you struggle with managing your studying time? Are you someone that uses the old \"I\'ll start it tomorrow\" phrase and then never does? Now is the time to change all that and by taking note of these 5 tips you can keep organised with your studies.\n<h2>Create a weekly timetable</h2>\nBy making a weekly timetable, you will then be able to work out and see your available time. You can then dedicate times and days you can study, whilst fitting it in with all your other commitments.\n<h2>Make a to-do list</h2>\nList all of the work you need to do and tick them off once you have completed them. You will then have an idea how close you are to finishing your studies.\n<h2>Urgent tasks</h2>\nPrioritise your work, by working out which tasks are more urgent than others. This in particular is a great method for those that are studying more than one course with us.\n<h2>Target setting</h2>\nMake decisions on how long to spend on each task and when it should be completed by. By sticking to deadlines you will then have an estimated date you will complete your studies.\n<h2>Splitting down work</h2>\nOrganise pieces of work such as: assignments and essays, into smaller and less daunting tasks. This will then make it easier for you to stay focused during your studying time.',NULL,NULL,9,'2015-12-09 10:08:26','2017-03-29 11:37:26',2,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4231',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(64,'5 WAYS TO MANAGE YOUR STUDYING TIME','4231-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"/storage/images/media_items/old_images/2015/12/time-management.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-4228\" src=\"/storage/images/media_items/old_images/2015/12/time-management-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"time-management\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n<ol>\n	<li><strong>Create a weekly timetable </strong></li>\n</ol>\nBy making a weekly timetable, you will then be able to work out and see your available time. You can then dedicate times and days you can study, whilst fitting it in with all your other commitments.\n\n&nbsp;\n<ol start=\"2\">\n	<li><strong>Make a to-do list</strong></li>\n</ol>\nList all of the work you need to do and tick them off once you have completed them. You will then have an idea how close you are to finishing your studies.\n\n&nbsp;\n<ol start=\"3\">\n	<li><strong>Urgent tasks</strong></li>\n</ol>\nPrioritise your work, by working out which tasks are more urgent than others. This in particular is a great method for those that are studying more than one course with us\n\n&nbsp;\n<ol start=\"4\">\n	<li><strong>Target setting</strong></li>\n</ol>\nMake decisions on how long to spend on each task and when it should be completed by. By sticking to deadlines you will then have an estimated date you will complete your studies.\n\n&nbsp;\n<ol start=\"5\">\n	<li><strong>Splitting down work </strong></li>\n</ol>\nOrganise pieces of work such as: assignments and essays, into smaller and less daunting tasks. This will then make it easier for you to stay focused.\n\n&nbsp;',NULL,NULL,9,'2015-12-09 09:54:59','2015-12-09 09:54:59',1,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/2015/12/09/4231-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(65,'10 simple ways to lose weight','10-ways-to-lose-the-pounds',NULL,NULL,'<em>Want some quick tips to lose weight? Our Active IQ fitness tutor, Sam Deeley, recently gave us his top tips to shed the pounds and get back in shape for the Spring</em>\n\n<h2>Take the Stairs</h2>\n\nA simple tip is to avoid those elevators! Statistics show that by using the stairs you burn 7 times more calories than taking the lift.\n\n<h2>Decrease your carbohydrate intake at night</h2>\n\nAt night you will not need to refuel your body, as you will be inactive. Therefore by cutting down your carbohydrate intake it will store less body fat.\n\n<h2>Eat those all-important Vegetables</h2>\n\nBy eating more vegetables, it will help you stay fuller for longer. This means snacking won?t be necessary. The best vegetables to eat include: Kale, Spinach and Broccoli.\n\n<h2>Don?t skip meals</h2>\n\nSkipping your meals will result in you eating more later on, as you?ll be hungrier. You should aim at eating six small meals a day. Also always remember to have a healthy breakfast, as you will be less likely to snack before lunch. Kick start your metabolism for the day!\n\n<h2>Do your maths </h2>\nIf you do your maths you could lose 1-2 lbs a week. You should aim at being in a 500-calorie deficit every day. For example: You may choose to eat 250 calories fewer than your recommended amount and then do a workout which burns another 250 calories. Just doing 30 minutes of exercise a day, can result in 100 calories being burned. That?s better than no calories!\n\n<h2>Hit the weights</h2>\n\nMuscle at rest burns more calories than fat at rest. Increasing your muscle mass helps you lose weight more efficiently. The more muscle you have, the more fat you will burn.\n\n<h2>Drink more water</h2>\nPut down all of those drinks which are full of calories such as milk, juices and soft drinks. Water has no calories, so drink more of the good stuff!\n\n<h2>Simple Swaps</h2>\n\nSwap those extra-large whole milk lattes or cappuccinos that are full of calories, for a regular size coffee with lower fat milk with fewer calories. It will also save you money! By swapping a big dinner plate to a smaller one, will mean eating a smaller portion. In addition it will look like you have more food on your plate too, bonus!\n<h2>Don?t be greedy</h2>\nOnce you have eaten your food, don?t go back for seconds. Feel satisfied not stuffed!\n\n<h2>Avoid the TV</h2>\nWhen eating in front of the TV we eat more without noticing or even enjoying it. Why not swap the TV for the table?',NULL,NULL,9,'2015-12-09 10:49:45','2017-03-13 14:12:36',2,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4239',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
