	(102,'How to study when you have children','how-to-study-when-you-have-children',NULL,NULL,'Studying when you have children can be difficult. Especially when you want to concentrate on your work and you can\'t, as your little monster keeps getting in the way! So here are a few tips to help you:\n<h2>Have confidence in yourself</h2>\nIf you have not studied for a while, don?t worry you still have the ability to study. Have confidence in yourself and you will achieve your dreams!\n<h2>Set aside some time to study</h2>\nAllocate yourself some study time. You will have assignments that are due in, so make sure you complete them and not leave them until the last minute. But don?t forget to set aside some time other than studying and give yourself a break. You should ask your family and friends to help you out whilst you study. For example: ask them to babysit or help out around the house so you can concentrate on your studies.\n<h2>Have a place to study</h2>\nHave your own space in your house which is dedicated to your studying. This should be strictly off limit to your child. You will then be able to leave all of your work out for later, without your child interfering. If you do not have a room that is dedicated to studying, you can put your work into a box and out the way, to keep it safe.\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<h2>Choosing when to study</h2>\nYou need to work out which part of the day best suits you to study. Are you a morning person or a night owl? Your studying will be the most effective when you are alert.\n<h2>Study with a partner</h2>\nIt would help if you could study with someone. As you are doing long distance learning you should make the most of forums and try and find someone that is also studying a long distance course nearby. You could even meet up and learn together. At the very least find someone close to home who can help you edit and review your work, and who is interested in listening to what you are doing.',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-03-17 13:22:11','2016-03-17 13:22:11',2,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4372',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(103,'','4372-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'<strong>Have confidence in yourself</strong>\n\nIf you have not studied for a while and you think that younger people have the edge, don?t worry you still have the ability to study. It is said that older students are the ones with the edge, as they are more mature and want to make the most of their time.\n\n<strong>Set aside some time to study</strong>\n\nAllocate yourself some study time. You will have assignments that are due in, so make sure you complete them before your deadlines. But don?t forget to set aside some time other than studying, to give yourself a break.<strong>\nHave a place to study</strong>\n\nHave your own space in your house which is dedicated to your studying. This should be strictly off limit to your child. You will then be able to leave all of your work out for later, without your child interfering. If you do not have a room that is dedicated to studying, you can put your work into a box and out the way, to keep it safe.\n\n<strong>Try not to fall behind</strong>\n\nAlthough you will be studying a distance learning course, try not to leave all of your studies till the last minute. Balance your work load out in order to keep on top of it. This will make it easier in the long run.\n\n<strong>Don?t set your expectations too high</strong>\n\nDo not put pressure on yourself by expecting the highest qualification, as this may be a little unrealistic. Make sure you have what it is to pass and anything else is a bonus.<strong>\n</strong><strong>Take time out to enjoy yourself and your child</strong>\n\nStudying is very time-consuming and you may find that you are missing out on your child?s growing up. Therefore you need to make sure you take time out from your studying and spend some time with your child.\n\n<strong>Ask for help</strong>\n\nAsk your family and friends to help you out whilst you study. For example: ask them to babysit or help out around the house so you can concentrate on your studies.\n\n<strong>Choosing when to study</strong>\n\nYou need to work out which part of the day best suits you to study. Are you a morning person or a night owl? Your studying will be the most effective when you are alert.\n\n<strong>Study with a partner </strong>\n\nIt would help if you could study with someone. As you are doing long distance learning you should make the most of forums and try and find someone that is also studying a long distance course nearby. You could even meet up and learn together. At the very least find someone close to home who can help you edit and review your work, and who is interested in listening to what you are doing.',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-04 11:54:28','2016-01-04 11:54:28',1,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/2016/01/04/4372-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(104,'How to tell if you are in the wrong job','wrong-job',NULL,NULL,'Do you ever wonder if you are in the right job for you? Take time to think about your work and whether you\'re happy with what you do. Here 3 different ways to tell if you are in the wrong job:\n<h2>Do you seek distractions at work?</h2>\nIf you would rather focus your time on distractions than getting your work done, then your job is not important to you. You should be paying attention to your work and enjoying it whilst completing it. If you don?t feel like you can enjoy your work, then you are in the wrong job or need a new project or change.\n<h2>Do you have no interest in engaging with your team?</h2>\nDo you get along with the people you work with? Maybe you have a personality conflict with them? Or maybe you have no idea why ? but you do not want to join in with discussions. Then you are in the wrong job. You spend the majority of your life at work with the same people, so if you can?t be yourself around them then you will find your job boring and awkward. It is your boss?s duty to make sure all of their staff are working as a team so if you have a problem talk to them!\n<h2>Are you doing it just for the money?</h2>\nThere is nothing wrong with loving the money you get from your job, but that shouldn\'t be the only reason you like your job. Your job should be in something you have passion for and which allows you to show off your talents. Ask yourself what would you do for the rest of your life for free? If this isn\'t your current job, you need to change your career path. Gaining a new qualification from home can help with this, without giving up you current job.\n\nSo why not take a look at our courses now!',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-15 16:15:24','2017-03-29 13:02:20',2,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4379',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(105,'How to tell if you are in the wrong job','4379-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'<strong>Do you seek distractions at work?</strong>\n\nIf you would rather focus your time on distractions than getting your work done, then your job is not important to you. You should be paying attention to your work and enjoying it whilst completing it. If you don?t feel like you can enjoy your work, then you are in the wrong job or need a new project or change.\n\n<strong>Do you have no interest in engaging with your team?</strong>\n\nDo you get along with the people you work with? Maybe you have a personality conflict with them? Or maybe you have no idea why ? but you do not want to join in with discussions. Then you are in the wrong job. You spend the majority of your life at work with the same people, so if you can?t be yourself around them then you will find your job boring and awkward. It is your boss?s duty to make sure all of their staff are working as a team so if you have a problem talk to them!\n\n<strong>Are you doing it just for the money?</strong>\n\nThere is nothing wrong with loving the money you get from your job, but that shouldn?t be the only reason you like your job. Your job should be in something you have passion for and which allows you to show off your talents. Ask yourself what would you do for the rest of your life for free? If this isn?t your current job, you need to change your career path. Gaining a new qualification from home can help with this, without giving up you current job.',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-04 12:01:10','2016-01-04 12:01:10',1,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/2016/01/04/4379-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(106,'Why a job in health and social care is rewarding','why-a-job-in-health-and-social-care-is-a-rewarding',NULL,NULL,'There are many different typesofjobs in health and social care, all of which are very rewarding careers. Here are more benefits why a job in this field isbeneficial:\n<h2>Positive outcomes</h2>\nOn a daily basis, there is an opportunity to make real differences to people?s lives and it is no surprise that job satisfaction in the profession is very high. You will be able to see how your help has given them a better future.\n<h2>Interacting with people</h2>\nYou come face to face with your patient. You will know who you are dealing with on a daily basis and build relationships with them. By actually listening to them open up about their experiences, will allow you to get to know the person and become close to them.\n<h2>Gaining new knowledge and skills</h2>\nThere is no day the same. There is a lot of variety in health and social jobs, as all patents have a different problem. Some problems you may not have come across before. Therefore you will be improving your skills and knowledge whilst on the job.\n<h2>People you work with</h2>\nThe people you work with ensure that days aren\'t dull and boring. You will be able to have a laugh and get to know people better. Also helping each other deal with different problems, means you will be developing your knowledge.\n\nIn order to be one step closer to pursuinga job in <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/care-skills_courses.html\">health and social care</a> why not enrol on one of our home distance learning courses now.\n\n<a class=\"blog-cta\" href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/care-skills_courses.html\">Take a look at our health and social care courses</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-15 13:28:27','2017-06-09 08:55:31',2,'http://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4381',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
