	(182,'How to win a chess match in 4 moves','4516-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'How to win a chess game in 4 moves\n\nIf you\'re facing another player who\'s just starting out and you\'re feeling cocky you could always try \'fool\'s mate.\'\n\nAssuming you\'re playing white, then your first move should be pawn to e4.\n\nThis trick relies on getting two pieces into an attack as quickly as possible and on black making some poor moves- basically white\'s queen captures the pawn diagonally to the right of the black King and another attacking piece backs up your queen.\n\nDiagram... Possibly an animated gif board?\n\nThis attack relies on black playing some poor opening moves and leaving no flight square for the king. It\'s almost certainly never going to present itself in a match against someone of a decent standard but it\'s quite funny to get away with it at least once.\n\nFools mate',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-08 14:45:46','2016-01-08 14:45:46',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/2016/01/08/4516-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(183,'3 Reasons why you should enrol on our advanced nutrition course','3-reasons-why-you-should-enrol-on-our-advanced-nutrition-course',NULL,NULL,'Are you interested in how to become specialised in advanced nutrition? Want to get an insight into why we crave certain foods and suffer from various eating disorders? Then our advanced nutrition and health course is for you!\n\nHere are 3reasons why you should boost your skills and enrol onour Level 3course today:\n<h2>Explore why we crave and why it is so hard to give up chocolate</h2>\nSome people may say cravings are all in our head, well they?re right! They are controlled mostly by the memory and sensory pleasure parts of the brain. Cravings are said to satisfy emotional needs such as stress and reduce anxiety. Most of our cravings are unhealthy and can do more harm than good. So put down that biscuit now!\n<h2>Learn about eating disorders and the effects</h2>\nEating disorders are becoming increasingly common. They are characterised by an abnormal attitude towards foods that cause someone to change their eating habits and behaviours.\n\nThe most common disorders include:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Anorexia Nervosa</li>\n 	<li>Bulimia</li>\n 	<li>Binge Eating Disorder</li>\n</ul>\nStatistics show that young people are most likely tohave an eating disorder, with the NUS revealing that the number of teenagers that have been admitted to hospital with an eating disorder has nearly doubled in three years!\n<h2>Explore the basis of the food combining system</h2>\nThe food combining system is based on the discovery that certain combinations of food may be digested with greater ease and efficiency than others. By combining correct foods, means health will improve as there is a smaller load on the digestive organs. Amazingly, it is stated that so-called food allergies can disappear when combining proper food together!\n\nEnrol on our<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/advanced-nutrition-and-health-3.html\">Advanced Nutrition and Health Level 3</a> course now!\n\n<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/advanced-nutrition-and-health-3.html\">Take a look at our Advanced Nutrition and Health Level 3 course&gt;&gt;</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-07-15 11:30:43','2016-07-15 11:33:51',2,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4523',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(184,'Crave success in our advanced nutrition course now!','4523-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'Are you interested in how to become specialised in advanced nutrition? Want to get an insight into why we crave certain foods and can suffer from eating disorders and obesity? Then our advanced nutrition course is for you!\n\nHere are three reasons why you should boost your skills by completing our advanced nutrition course:\n\n<strong>Explore why we crave and why it is so hard to give up chocolate</strong>\n\nSome people may say cravings are all in our head, well they?re right! They are controlled mostly by the memory and sensory pleasure parts of the brain. Cravings are said to satisfy emotional needs such as stress and reduce anxiety. Most of our cravings are unhealthy and can do more harm than good. So put down that biscuit now!\n\n<strong>Learn about eating disorders and the effects</strong>\n\nEating disorders are becoming increasingly common. They are characterised by an abnormal attitude towards foods that cause someone to change their eating habits and behaviours.\n\nThe most common disorders include:\n<ul>\n	<li>Anorexia Nervosa</li>\n	<li>Bulimia</li>\n	<li>Binge Eating Disorder</li>\n</ul>\nYoung people are the majority that have an eating disorder. The media may have an effect on some people by conveying people to be thin. This results into people thinking that they should be this way.\n\n<strong>Explore the basis of the food combining system</strong>\n\nThe food combining system is based on the discovery that certain combinations of food may be digested with greater ease and efficiency than others. By combining the correct foods, means health will improve, as there is a smaller load on the digestive organs. Amazingly, it is stated that so-called food allergies can disappear when combining proper food together.\n\nTo learn more enrol now on our advanced nutrition course &gt;&gt;',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-11 12:47:37','2016-01-11 12:47:37',1,'https://blog.openstudycolle