	(213,'Survey reveals later learners likely to earn more','the-surprising-reality-of-home-ownership-in-britain-the-most-qualified-buy-later-and-live-in-cheaper-homes',NULL,NULL,'THE SURPRISING REALITY OF HOME OWNERSHIP IN BRITAIN.  THE MOST QUALIFIED BUY LATER ? AND LIVE IN CHEAPER HOMES\n\n       Study shows that 75% of graduates will go on to own a home and car, compared to 85% of people who do a vocational qualification later in life\n       Graduate home ownership levels will be only 7% higher than amongst those who leave school at 16 years old (68%)\n       Plus, mature students will go on to own homes with an average value of 500,000 ? over twice the national average -  compared to the country?s graduates whose houses are worth just under 300,000\n       Is this because students never settle - taking nearly twice as many holidays a year by their forties as those who return to study - or because student debts are hampering home owning dreams?\n\nGraduates harbouring home owning dreams were dealt another blow today after a study showed they are 10% less likely to go on to own a home than those who quit school at 16 years old and return to vocational study later in life.\n\nAccording to the report, 48% of the country?s graduates will own a home by their forties, compared to 55% of those who return to education, either part or full time, and 52% of those who finish school early. By the age of 51, 85% of ?mature? students will be homeowners, compared to 75% of typical graduates and 68% of early leavers.\n\nAnd it isn?t a case of last but by no means least with those returning to education set to have a mean property value of just over 500,000 by 51 compared to just under 300,000 at the same age amongst degree holders, based on current house prices.\n\nA total of 1,000 Britons were surveyed to compile the figures, with the results then used to build a General Linear Regression model ? which takes variables from a survey to predict likely outcomes.\n\nDr David Lewis, director of research of Mindlab who delivered the study for Open Study College, said: ?I conducted this research for Open Study College and the findings were quite fascinating.  We expected to find that graduates would have the greatest share of property ownership over the age of 4o, and the smallest under the age of 30, but this was not true.  They were the most likely, by a margin of a few percent, to own a home by the age of 30 - albeit in very small numbers - but began to get left behind as they entered their forties with both the ?unqualified? and ?mature? students ? those we dubbed Newdents ? surpassing them and buying homes, whilst they rented or stayed with parents.?\n\nThe study also found that later learners are more likely to be in a better paid role and to hold director or managerial positions.   Dr Lewis added; ?Obviously, this makes saving for a deposit and paying a mortgage much easier.  Interestingly, this group also holiday less which again suggests that they are sensible with money.\n\n?After abandoning my medical studies while in my early 20s, I spent more than a decade working in the ?real? world before returning to university as a mature student. Later, when lecturing at the University of Sussex, I found older students typically possessed a significantly greater desire to learn than those straight from school. This ambition obviously translates into all areas of their life ? from work to family and home.?\n\nSteven Nash, at Open Study College, said; ?The difficulty for young people going straight to university is that they are often not at the right stage in their lives to start planning their career or home life.\n\n?Degrees are chosen on the basis of what we think we might like and want to do ? at the age of 18.  This means the first few years after graduating aren?t as productive in terms of earning and life progression as they might be.\n\n?In contrast, many of the people we see returning to study have a clear focus, whether it?s a promotion at work to help them save for a house deposit, or to retrain for a completely new career to increase job satisfaction.\n\n?In my view though, the real differences between the continuous and late studiers, is debt.  The demand for distance and online learning is growing at an incredible pace because it doesn?t cost 30,000 to get a qualification.  The digital age has obviously helped with this ? people are used to shopping and banking online, so why not learn too?  But above all, it?s cheaper to learn this way ? and, it would seem, more financially beneficial long term.?\n\nFor more information on Open Study College please visit www.openstudycollege.com.\n',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-20 15:12:19','2016-01-20 15:12:19',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4634',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(214,'Survey reveals later learners likely to earn more','4634-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'THE SURPRISING REALITY OF HOME OWNERSHIP IN BRITAIN.  THE MOST QUALIFIED BUY LATER ? AND LIVE IN CHEAPER HOMES\n\n       Study shows that 75% of graduates will go on to own a home and car, compared to 85% of people who do a vocational qualification later in life\n       Graduate home ownership levels will be only 7% higher than amongst those who leave school at 16 years old (68%)\n       Plus, mature students will go on to own homes with an average value of 500,000 ? over twice the national average -  compared to the country?s graduates whose houses are worth just under 300,000\n       Is this because students never settle - taking nearly twice as many holidays a year by their forties as those who return to study - or because student debts are hampering home owning dreams?\n\nGraduates harbouring home owning dreams were dealt another blow today after a study showed they are 10% less likely to go on to own a home than those who quit school at 16 years old and return to vocational study later in life.\n\nAccording to the report, 48% of the country?s graduates will own a home by their forties, compared to 55% of those who return to education, either part or full time, and 52% of those who finish school early. By the age of 51, 85% of ?mature? students will be homeowners, compared to 75% of typical graduates and 68% of early leavers.\n\nAnd it isn?t a case of last but by no means least with those returning to education set to have a mean property value of just over 500,000 by 51 compared to just under 300,000 at the same age amongst degree holders, based on current house prices.\n\nA total of 1,000 Britons were surveyed to compile the figures, with the results then used to build a General Linear Regression model ? which takes variables from a survey to predict likely outcomes.\n\nDr David Lewis, director of research of Mindlab who delivered the study for Open Study College, said: ?I conducted this research for Open Study College and the findings were quite fascinating.  We expected to find that graduates would have the greatest share of property ownership over the age of 4o, and the smallest under the age of 30, but this was not true.  They were the most likely, by a margin of a few percent, to own a home by the age of 30 - albeit in very small numbers - but began to get left behind as they entered their forties with both the ?unqualified? and ?mature? students ? those we dubbed Newdents ? surpassing them and buying homes, whilst they rented or stayed with parents.?\n\nThe study also found that later learners are more likely to be in a better paid role and to hold director or managerial positions.   Dr Lewis added; ?Obviously, this makes saving for a deposit and paying a mortgage much easier.  Interestingly, this group also holiday less which again suggests that they are sensible with money.\n\n?After abandoning my medical studies while in my early 20s, I spent more than a decade working in the ?real? world before returning to university as a mature student. Later, when lecturing at the University of Sussex, I found older students typically possessed a significantly greater desire to learn than those straight from school. This ambition obviously translates into all areas of their life ? from work to family and home.?\n\nSteven Nash, at Open Study College, said; ?The difficulty for young people going straight to university is that they are often not at the right stage in their lives to start planning their career or home life.\n\n?Degrees are chosen on the basis of what we think we might like and want to do ? at the age of 18.  This means the first few years after graduating aren?t as productive in terms of earning and life progression as they might be.\n\n?In contrast, many of the people we see returning to study have a clear focus, whether it?s a promotion at work to help them save for a house deposit, or to retrain for a completely new career to increase job satisfaction.\n\n?In my view though, the real differences between the continuous and late studiers, is debt.  The demand for distance and online learning is growing at an incredible pace because it doesn?t cost 30,000 to get a qualification.  The digital age has obviously helped with this ? people are used to shopping and banking online, so why not learn too?  But above all, it?s cheaper to learn this way ? and, it would seem, more financially beneficial long term.?\n\nFor more information on Open Study College please visit www.openstudycollege.com.\n',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-01-20 15:12:19','2016-01-20 15:12:19',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/2016/01/20/4634-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
