	(304,'How To Concentrate Whilst Studying','how-to-concentrate-whilst-studying',NULL,NULL,'Do you find it hard to study? Get bored easily and then give up? Then here are 5 tips on how to concentrate whilst studying:\n<h2>Place to study</h2>\nConsider a quiet and suitable environment for studying. This room should be silent and free of distractions, whether it?s your bedroom or the library. You will need to be comfy and have good lighting. It is better if you sit in a chair at a table or desk and avoid studying in bed, as you will just want to go to sleep. Make sure you don?t sit right in front of a TV, as you will become easily distracted.\n<h2>Make sure you have everything you need to study</h2>\nBefore you sit down to start studying you should gather all of your materials you need. Make sure that all of your pens, pencils, highlighters and books are all in arms reach. This should not interrupt your studying time and concentration. Only use your computer if it is entirely needed, if notmore it away.\n<h2>Turn mobiles off</h2>\nTurn your mobile off when studying to avoid temptation. Phones are the biggest distraction and can have a detrimental effect on your learning. By switching them off will allow you to concentrate solely on your course materials without wasting precious time.\n<h2>Make a timetable</h2>\nPlan your study time and aim to work for 30-60 minutes with a 5-10 minute break in between. This will allow your brain to recharge. If you are studying more than one course then you should try to switch them regularly, to prevent yourself from becoming bored. A new subject will wake up your mind and generatemotivation.\n<h2>Consider playing music</h2>\nSome people find that music helps them concentrate, whereas for some people it doesn\'t. You should consider trying this out to see if it works for you. Listening to music will make studying more enjoyable. Although you may want to consider other genres of music, as the music that you listen to may not be right for studying.',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-04-19 11:11:57','2016-04-19 11:11:57',2,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=4995',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(305,'How To Concentrate Whilst Studying','4995-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'Do you find it hard to study? Get bored easily and then give up? Then here are 5 tips on how to concentrate whilst studying:\n\n<h2>Place to study</h2>\n\nConsider a quiet and suitable environment for studying. This room should be silent and free of distractions, whether it?s your bedroom or the library. You will need to be comfy and have good lighting in the place where you study. It is better if you sit in a chair at a table or desk and avoid studying in bed, as you will just want to go to sleep. Make sure you don?t sit right in front of a TV, as you will become easily distracted.\n\n<h2>Make sure you have everything you need to study</h2>\n\nBefore you sit down to start studying you should gather all of your materials you need to study. Make sure that all of your pens, pencils, highlighters and books are all in arms reach. This should not interrupt your studying time and concentration. Only use your computer if it is entirely needed, if not keep it away from you.\n\n<h2>Turn mobiles off</h2>\n\nTurn your mobile off when studying to avoid temptation. Phones are the biggest distraction and can have a detrimental effect on your learning. By switching them off will allow you to concentrate solely on your course materials without wasting time on them.\n\n<h2>Make a timetable</h2>\n\nPlan your study time and aim to work for 30-60 minutes with a 5-10 minute break in between. This will allow your brain to recharge. If you are studying more than one course then you should try to switch them regularly, to prevent yourself from becoming bored. A new subject will wake up your mind and your motivation.\n\n<h2>Consider playing music </h2>\n\nSome people find that music helps them concentrate, whereas for some people it doesn\'t. You should consider trying this out to see if it works for you. Listening to music will make studying more enjoyable. Although you may want to consider other genres of music, as the music that you listen to may not be right for you when studying.',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-03-29 10:25:19','2016-03-29 10:25:19',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/2016/03/29/4995-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
