	(490,'Fancy being a Chessmaster? Here are 5 tips on playing chess','5-tips-playing-chess',NULL,NULL,'Do you like playing chess but get fed of up losing all the time? Then now is the time to wave goodbye to those days and start winning with those killer moves. Take note of these 5 tips on how to play better chess:\n\n<h2>Try to dominate the centre of the board</h2>\nYou should try and dominate the centre of the board and allow yourself space to develop your important attacking pieces.\n\nA classic first move that you should make is to move the pawn in front of either the king or queen 2 squares forward. This allows you to open up space for your bishops and queen to enter the game. Failing to do this will mean your pawns block you from advancing your important attacking pieces and they won?t be able to play.\n<h2>Move your knights and bishops</h2>\nBefore moving your queen, rooks or king, move your knights and bishops toward the centre of the board. You want to get these pieces out from behind the pawns so they can attack.\n<h2>Think strategically</h2>\nYou need to have your thinking cap on throughout the whole game. Try to understand what your opponents last move did, what they are up to and if they are laying traps to capture your pieces. With this in mind decide on your own plan and always look at all of your possibilities. You should always figure out moves that will threaten your opponent?s king first.\n<h2>Don?t play too fast</h2>\nEven if you see a good move, stop and look. Is there a better move? Patience is the key to playing a great move and can be the difference between you winning or losing the game. So always double-check your moves and make sure it doesn?t leave anything unprotected.\n<h2>Try looking at the board from your opponents perspective</h2>\nTry flipping the board around and look at the game from your opponents perspective.  If you were your opponent, what attacking threats can you develop?\n\nAre you ready to take on your new challenge in chess?\n\nMaybe you need that extra boost to strategically think like a professional?\n\nOr perhaps you?ve never played chess before and want to take on a new skill?\n\nThen that?s where our <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/chess-2.html\">Chess Level 2 course</a> can help you!\n\n<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/chess-2.html\" class=\"blog-cta\">Take a look at our Chess Level 2 course today!</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-07-05 11:24:02','2017-03-06 13:14:23',2,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=5649',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(491,'5 tips on how to become a chess champ','5649-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'Do you like to play chess but fed of up losing all the time? Then now is the time to wave goodbye to those days and start winning with those killer moves. Take note of these 5 tips on how you can become a chess champ:\n\n<h2>Learn the moves</h2>\n\nAs every chess piece travels in a certain way, knowing these can help in attacking your opponent. For instance, a pawn moves straight ahead but only attacks on an angle, one square at a time (apart from on the opening move where it can be moved 2 squares forward) So get studying your pieces now!\n\n<h2>Always open with a pawn</h2>\n\nA crucial first move that you should always make is moving the pawn in front of either the king or queen 2 squares forward. This allows you to open ways for your bishops and queen to enter the game. Failing to do this will mean your pawns will be in the way and they won?t be able to play.\n\n<h2>Move your knights and bishops out</h2>\n\nBefore moving your queen, rooks or king, move your knights and bishops toward the centre of the board. You want to get these pieces out from behind the pawns so they can attack.\n\n<h2>Think strategically</h2>\n\nYou need to have your thinking cap on throughout the whole game. Try to understand what your opponents last move did, what they are up to and if they are laying traps to capture your pieces. With this in mind decide on your own plan and always look at all of your possibilities. You should always figure out moves that will threaten your opponent?s king first.\n\n<h2>Don?t play too fast</h2>\n\nEven if you see a good move, stop and look. Is there a better move? Patience is the key to playing a great move and can be the difference between you winning or losing the game. So always double-check your moves and make sure it doesn?t leave anything unprotected.\n\nAre you ready to take on your new challenge in chess?\n\nMaybe you need that extra boost to strategically think like a professional?\n\nOr perhaps you?ve never played chess before and want to take on a new skill?\n\nThen that?s where our Chess Level 2 course can help you!\n\nTake a look at our Chess Level 2 Course today!',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-07-05 11:06:02','2016-07-05 11:06:02',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/2016/07/05/5649-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
