	(495,'5 Tips for balancing work and your studies','5-tips-for-balancing-work-and-studies',NULL,NULL,'Studying an extra qualification can help you achieve that needed next step in your career path. You will be able to bring new skills to the workplace and open up a range of opportunities. However many people struggle with studying and working, which is why balancing these is very important. Take a look at these 5 tips on how you can balance work and your studies:\n<h2>Develop a plan</h2>\nYou need to develop a realistic plan that takes into account:\n<ul>\n 	<li>How many hours a week you are prepared to study</li>\n 	<li>How many days a week and hours you work</li>\n 	<li>Whether you want to complete your studies as quickly as possible or at a steady place</li>\n 	<li>Your goals</li>\n 	<li>Your personality</li>\n</ul>\nWith this in mind create a plan that can help you stay organised throughout your studies.\n<h2>Prioritise</h2>\nDecide on your priorities and accept that somethings will have to give ? and not just the house cleaning! Your job will be your main commitment so fit your studying around it and maybe pass on the occasional social gathering with friends.\n<h2>Work smarter</h2>\nThe last thing you want to do when it comes to your studying is waste time. If you feel like you have been studying for hours and you still haven?t learnt a thing then your learning method is not working for you. Maybe try: mind mapping, marking your course materials, making a list, keeping a list of questions, using sticky notes, drawing diagrams and doodles, colour co-ordinating and writing down key information. You need to find the best study technique that suits you.\n<h2>Manage stress</h2>\nWorking and studying can be very stressful, which is why it is very important to take regular breaks. You should aim to have a 5-10 minute break after every hour of studying. It is also vital for you to get plenty of sleep and stay physically active in order to rest and freshen your brain.\n<h2>Focus on your goals</h2>\nYou need to remember why you have taken on the challenge of a new course. Maybe it?s for a promotion and you want to climb the career ladder? Or to achieve a new career? Whatever it may be focus on your goals and think about your accomplishments when you?ve completed your course.',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-07-15 15:01:28','2016-07-15 15:01:28',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=5667',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
