	(672,'The truth about your brains learning system','the-truth-about-your-brains-learning-system',NULL,NULL,'With our brains being the most complex organ in the human body, understanding how we think, learn and do things is fascinating. So check out these 5 facts about how our brains learn best:\n<h2>Having good night?s sleep helps learning</h2>\nStatistics show that those who have more than 8 hours sleep learn information better than those that don?t, with an increased improvement of 20.5%. It has also been found that napping in between completing studying can improve learning. When a memory first gets recorded into the brain it can be easily be forgotten. Sleeping pushes these memories into the brains long term storage, avoiding them to be replaced. So if you?re struggling to study, take a good night?s sleep and prepare your brain for learning the following day!\n<h2>We learn better if it?s visual</h2>\nDid you know that half of your brain power uses its resources on vision? This means that 50% of your brains resources turn what you see into information. With vision being the main one of our senses used to take in information, using our eyes actually helps us learn better. Why not try if your learning improves by adding doodles, photos and drawings to your study notes?\n<h2>Exercise can help our long-term memory</h2>\nCompared to those that don?t exercise, those that do have a better long-term memory, attention span and problem-solving skills. When we exercise we release a protein called Brain-Derived Neurotrophic Factor which makes us feel at ease and happy.\n<h2>We relate information</h2>\nOur brain stores new information if it already has something to relate it to. Therefore it is best to study the big picture of the concept before trying to learn all of the small details. Your brain stores and links this new information with existing ideas, which makes learning easier.',NULL,NULL,9,'2016-10-20 13:31:57','2016-10-20 13:31:57',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=6095',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
