	(999,'How to speed read','4395-autosave-v1',NULL,NULL,'Do you wish you could read fast and understand the information at the same time? Then you can do this by teaching yourself how to speed read, which will help when you are studying. Here are a few tips on how to speed read\n<h2>Stop talking to yourself</h2>\nThe majority of readers move their throats as if they were speaking the words. By doing this it slows down the speed you can read information. To prevent this from happening, you should chew gum or hum whilst reading.\n<h2>Hide words you?ve already read</h2>\nWhen reading you should cover the text that you have already read, as your eyes often move back to earlier words. This does not improve any understanding. If your eyes jump back to several lines behind, that is a sign you need to slow down.\n<h2>Understand eye movements</h2>\nIt has been proven that we can only read when our eyes have stopped moving. Your eyes move jerkily, skipping and stopping on random words. You should improve this line by line (although this may be difficult at first!). Studies show that you can read eight letters to the right of your eye position and four to the left. This works out to two or three words at a time.\n<h2>Make fewer eye movements</h2>\nYour brain decides where to move your eyes. It looks at how long or familiar the following words look. If you train your eyes to move to specific places on the page, it will allow you to read faster.\n<h2>Set a pace faster than you can understand</h2>\nIn order to become fast at reading and being able to understand the information, you need to set your pace faster than you would normally read. By doing this it will allow you to understand the main points quicker. Why not practice with this small exercise:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Whilst reading a piece of text, in your head say ?one one thousand? calmly. You should aim to finish the quote at the same time as finishing a line from the piece of text. Even if you don?t understand anything to begin with, this will help speed up your eye movement. You should keep repeating this whilst getting faster.</li>\n</ul>',NULL,NULL,9,'2017-03-29 13:48:39','2017-03-29 13:48:39',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/4395-autosave-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(1000,'Develop your knowledge in understanding autism','4507-autosave-v1',NULL,NULL,'Autism is becoming increasingly common. It is a lifelong developmental disability that affects how a person communicates and relates to other people. Here\'s why you shoulddevelop your knunderstanding of autism:\n\nPeople with itstruggle to make sense of people, places and events. The slightest thing could cause them anxiety. Even taking part in everyday family and social life can be hard for them.\n\nThere are many characteristics of autism, some of these include:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Love of routines</li>\n 	<li>Sensory sensitivity</li>\n 	<li>Special interests</li>\n 	<li>Learning difficulties</li>\n</ul>\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>?Everyday a young person with autism would visit a day service. He would always be dropped off by a taxi and knock the door before he was let in. One day, the door opened before he knocked. It caused confusion and was out of the ordinary. This made him return to the taxi to start the routine again.\"</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\nUnderstanding why people with autism behave in this manner can be very interesting. That?s why with our <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/understanding-autism-3.html\">understanding autism course</a> you can get an insight into how they think.\n\nBoost your understanding of autism in our Level course!\n\n<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/understanding-autism-3.html\">Take a look at our Understanding Autism Level 3 Course now &gt;&gt;</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2017-03-29 13:56:17','2017-03-29 13:56:17',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/4507-autosave-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
