	(1335,'How to improve your mental wellbeing ? our top tips!','improve-mental-wellbeing-top-tips',NULL,NULL,'It?s important to look after your mental wellbeing as your mental health is dependent on it. When you find that your mental wellbeing has started to decline, it can be difficult to know how to improve it. But, hopefully,our toptips can help you to improve your mental wellbeing and feel better about yourself.\n<h2>Look after yourself</h2>\nIt\'s important to treat yourself and your body right to maintain mental wellbeing. A poor diet, smoking and drinking alcohol can all negatively affect your state of mind. For this reason, it is important to fuel your body with a nutritious diet and look after yourself properly. You also need to make sure you are getting enough sleep, because getting too much or too little can have a huge impact on how you feel mentally.\n<h2>Be active</h2>\nExercise isn?t just great for your physical health, but your mental health too! There are close links between being physically active and your mental wellbeing. That doesn?t mean that you need to spend hours in the gym every day either? it could simply be getting outdoors and having a stroll on your lunch break, or going for a swim. Basically, find a physical activity that you enjoy and try to do it a few times a week, and you will feel much better for it!\n<h2>Socialise</h2>\nSocial interactions and good relationships are key to maintaining your mental health. This is because spending time with friends, family and the wider community helps you to feel happier and more secure. Human beings are social by nature, and building relationships with those around you help to improve your sense of belonging, and remove any feelings of isolation and loneliness.\n<h2>Set goals</h2>\nAre you finding that you have too much to do? Maybe you don?t know where to start? Or, there could be factors in your life that are stressing you out, such as money worries. Stress is not good for our mental health so it?s important that you identify what is causing your stress. A great way to deal with these stress factors and improve your mental wellbeing, is to set yourself achievable goals. Once you have your goal in mind, sit down and write a plan on how you are going to achieve your goal. You\'ll start to feel more relax, knowing that you have a plan to tackle the source of your stress.\n<h2>Keep learning</h2>\nAccording to the NHS, it is vital that we continue to learn throughout our lives to maintain our mental health and wellbeing. Learning something new could be something as big as learning a new language, or as simple as learning how to bakesomething new. Learning a new skill boosts your confidence, makes you happier and is great for your mental health... so, learning something new is officially good for you!\n\nTo find out more about improving your mental wellbeing, go to <a href=\"https://www.mind.org.uk/\">Mind?s website.</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2017-10-10 12:42:34','2017-10-10 12:42:34',2,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=7591',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(1336,'3 Reasons To Become A Forensic Scientist','3-reasons-become-forensic-scientist',NULL,NULL,'Are you cut out to be a forensic scientist?\n\nDoes the idea of uncovering crimes and helping to catch dangerous criminals appeal to you?\n\nAre you quick-witted and have a logically-wired brain?\n\nThen here are 3 reasons why this may just be the career for you?\n<h1><strong>Protect the public</strong></h1>\nA forensic scientist increases public safety by contributing to the capture of dangerous criminals. They help to achieve justice for victims and their families by using a range of techniques: DNA analysis, psychological theories and profiling approaches. With new developments, it is now possible for forensic scientists to solve crimes that have remained unsolved for years.\n\nYou might say they were the local heroes of the criminology world?\n<h1><strong>Career opportunities</strong></h1>\nThere are many exciting career opportunities within forensic science!\n\nYou can specialise in a range of different areas or get involved in them all. You can choose to become a fingerprint officer, criminal intelligence analyst, or even a toxicologist.\n\nThe career benefits are even better. As well as being recognised for your work in documented journals or at industry conferences, work your way up the ladder and you could earn up to 40,000!\n<h1><strong>Notwo days are the same</strong></h1>\nEvery investigation and crime scene is different so your tasks will differ day to day. You could be visiting a crime scene and taking photographs one day, while the next you could be in the lab exploring links between suspects and the criminal activity. You will also have to reconstruct crime scenes based on your scientific findings. So you can ensure that you?ll never have a dull day.\n\nKick-start your career on our<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/forensic-science-level-3.html\">Level 3 Forensic Science course!</a>\n\n<a class=\"blog-cta\" href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/forensic-science-level-3.html\">Take a look at our Forensic Science Level 3 course</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2017-11-22 12:03:32','2017-11-22 12:03:47',2,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=7592',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(1337,'How to improve your mental wellbeing ? our top tips!','7591-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'It?s important to look after your mental wellbeing as your mental health is dependent on it. When you find that your mental wellbeing has started to decline, it can be difficult to know how to improve it. But, hopefully, these six tips can help you to improve your mental wellbeing and feel better about yourself.\n<h2>Look after yourself</h2>\nIt is important to treat yourself and your body right to maintain mental wellbeing. A poor diet, smoking or drinking alcohol can all negatively affect your state of mind. For this reason, it is important to fuel your body with a nutritious diet and look after it. You also need to make sure you are getting enough sleep, because getting too much or too little can have a huge impact on how you feel mentally.\n<h2>Be active</h2>\nExercise isn?t just great for your physical health, but your mental health too! There are close links between being physically active and your mental wellbeing. That doesn?t mean that you need to spend hours in the gym every day either? it could simply be getting outdoors and having a stroll on your lunch break, or going for a swim. Basically, find a physical activity that you enjoy and try to do it a few times a week, and you will feel much better for it!\n<h2>Socialise</h2>\nSocial interactions and good relationships are key to maintaining your mental health. This is because spending time with friends, family and the wider community helps you to feel happier and more secure. Human beings are social by nature, and building relationships with those around you help to improve your sense of belonging, and remove any feelings of isolation and loneliness.\n<h2>Set goals</h2>\nAre you finding that you have too much to do? Maybe you don?t know where to start? Or, there could be factors in your life that are stressing you out, such as money worries. Stress is not good for our mental health so it?s important that you identify what is causing your stress. A great way to deal with these stress factors and improve your mental wellbeing, is to set yourself achievable goals. Once you have your goal in mind, sit down and write a plan on how you are going to achieve your goal. You can now relax, knowing that you have a plan to tackle the source of your stress.\n<h2>Keep learning</h2>\nAccording to the NHS, it is vital that we continue to learn throughout our lives to maintain our mental health and wellbeing. Learning something new, whether you learn a new language, or how to bake, or you take a photography course, boosts your confidence and your mental wellbeing. So it?s official, learning a new skill or gaining new knowledge makes you happier and is good for you!\n\nTo find out more about improving your mental wellbeing, go to <a href=\"https://www.mind.org.uk/\">Mind?s website.</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2017-10-10 12:27:46','2017-10-10 12:27:46',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/7591-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(1338,'3 Reasons to become a forensic scientist','7592-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'Have you ever thought about becoming a forensic scientist? Do you like the idea of uncovering crimes and helping catch dangerous criminals? Then a career as a forensic scientist would be perfect for you! Here?s 3 reasons why:\n<h2>Protect the public</h2>\nThe work forensic scientists do directly contribute to the capture of dangerous criminals and therefore increase safety for the public. They help gain justice for victims and their families, by using a range of techniques including DNA analysis, psychological theories and profiling approaches. With new developments it is now possible for forensic scientists to solve crimes that have remained unsolved for years.\n<h2>Career opportunities</h2>\nThere are many exciting career opportunities within forensic science. You may want to specialise into a specific field such as identifying murder weapons or analysing trace evidence found at the scene. You can also choose to become a fingerprint officer, criminal intelligence analyst or toxicologist. When you become experienced within this field you could earn up to 40,000! A forensic scientist may also document their research and findings in journal articles or at industry conferences.\n<h2>No day is the same</h2>\nEvery investigation and crime scene is different so your tasks will differ day to day. You could be visiting a crime scene and taking photographs one day, while the next you could be in the lab exploring links between suspects and the criminal activity. You will also have to reconstruct crime scenes based on your scientific findings.\n\nKick-start your career on our <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/forensic-science-level-3.html\">Level 3 Forensic Science course!</a>\n\n<a class=\"blog-cta\" href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/forensic-science-level-3.html\">Take a look at our Forensic Science Level course</a>',NULL,NULL,9,'2017-10-10 12:28:06','2017-10-10 1