	(1846,'How do I become a counsellor?','become-a-counsellor',NULL,NULL,'As one of the most popular careers in the UK, there are different entry points to become a counsellor.\n\nFor many, counselling is a second or third career choice, but others choose it as their primary career to achieve a more focused goal.\n\nYou may choose to specify in a preferred sector or remain neutral and stay open to a broad spectrum of counselling clients.\n\nThe role of a counsellor is to listen, understand and provide appropriate solutions to those experiencing problems in all aspects of life. The most common forms of counselling are:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Grief counselling</li>\n 	<li>Relationship counselling</li>\n 	<li>Behavioural counselling</li>\n</ul>\nAlthough each of these are different, they require the same set of basic skills in order to succeed. Currently there is no statutory regulation within this field, but you <em>can</em> improve your chances and career prospects?\n<h2><strong>Step One: Primary Education</strong></h2>\nLike most professional and vocational careers, to become a counsellor you will need a basic set of primary education. This will include:\n<ul>\n 	<li>GCSEs</li>\n 	<li>A Levels</li>\n 	<li>An undergraduate degree</li>\n</ul>\nThis education sets the foundation for your learning and helps you to progress further within this chosen field. We offer both a range of <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/qualifications/igcse\"><strong><u>GCSEs</u></strong></a> and <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/qualifications/a-level\"><strong><u>A Levels</u></strong></a> to help kickstart your career.\n<h2><strong>Step Two: Gaining Experience </strong></h2>\nIt is often beneficial to gain some form of experience when you wish to become a counsellor as it is a very competitive industry, so education alone will not be enough.\n\nDepending on the type of counselling you wish to pursue, you could choose to volunteer in a school to develop a deeper understanding of children, or perhaps a local community/youth centre to interact with a range of different people.\n<h2><strong>Step Three: Enhance your education</strong></h2>\nOnce you?ve got the basic steps out the way, the next thing to do is to make yourself stand out from the crowd with further education.\n\nThis is where you can choose to specify your training or simply add additional qualifications and courses to your CV. For example:\n\n<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/cie-therapeutic-person-centred-counsel-5.html\"><strong><u>CIE Level 5 Diploma in Therapeutic Person-centred Counselling </u></strong></a>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/addiction-counselling.html\"><strong><u>Addiction Counselling </u></strong></a>\n\n<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/courses/grief-counselling-3.html\"><strong><u>Grief Counselling Level 3</u></strong></a>\n\nAll of these courses allow you to further understand what is needed to become a counsellor as well as improving your employability and advancing your career; and this is just the start.\n\nTake a look at our <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/pages/how-it-works.html\"><strong><u>website</u></strong></a> to see all of our courses. Or give our Student Adviser team a call on <strong>03300 563 100</strong> and decide which is best for your future as a counsellor.',NULL,NULL,9,'2018-06-11 11:12:41','2018-06-11 11:12:41',2,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=8567',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
