	(1941,'The Ultimate Guide to Results Day','8755-autosave-v1',NULL,NULL,'Waiting for results can be one of the most nerve-wracking times of your life. Maybe you?re excited because you think you?ve done well, or dreading it because you?re worried that you\'ve failed. It?s a very anxious time.\n\nWhichever bracket you fall into, you will still need to know what results day entails, and how to best be prepared for it.\n<h2><strong>Before Results Day</strong></h2>\n<h3>Relax.</h3>\nIt may be easier said than done, but stressing isn\'t going to change what grade you have. You?ve already sat the exams so there is nothing more you can do.<a href=\"https://blog.openstudycollege.com/enjoy-summer-results-day/\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Enjoy the rest of your summer</span></a> and make the most of your free time.\n<h3>Have all the necessary information</h3>\nMost results days are held at your school or college, so it will be useful to know things such as what time it will be open or which entrance to use. However, if you study through distance learning, you may be receiving your results by email, in which case it is handy to know when and ensure that you have access to a computer at the time.\n<h3>Be prepared for all outcomes</h3>\nIt is best to be objective in situations like this. Don?t assume you are going to fail but be aware of the possibilities if this does happen. Are you going to go through Clearing? Are you going to take a year out? Or are you going to look at other options available? Have a clear idea of how you will approach this situation should it occur.\n<h2><strong>On Results Day</strong></h2>\n<h3>Stay calm.</h3>\nRegardless of what happens, stay calm. Like we said, there is nothing you can do to change the results. But there is always something you can do to change what happens after you receive your results.\n<h3>Don?t make any rash decisions.</h3>\nWhen students don?t receive the grades they want, they can panic and do the quickest thing possible that seems like a good idea. Luckily, if you follow our guide to results day, you will already be prepared and know the options available to you, so this shouldn?t be an issue.\n<h3>If you get your expected results?</h3>\n<strong>CONGRATULATIONS!</strong> All that hard work has paid off!\n\nIf you have studied GCSEs, then ensure your place at your college or sixth form is confirmed. Some places have entry requirements so it is best to make sure.\n\nIf you have done your A Levels and are planning to go to university, then check UCAS track as this will have confirmation of your place and the instructions on how to confirm.\n\nBut if you aren?t planning on going to university or study your A Levels, check out the other options available to you, such as distance learning courses, apprenticeships or work schemes.\n<h3>If you didn?t get your expected results?</h3>\nDon?t worry, there is always an option. For all you know, your study establishmentmay have still offered you a place, so you should still check to know what to do next.\n\nIf you are not offered a place, there are a few options available to you:\n<ul>\n 	<li><strong>Apply to university</strong><strong> through Clearing</strong> ? UCAS will match your grades with various university courses to find you a place.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Resit your exams and defer for a year</strong> ? it is okay to notprogress immediatelyafter school or college. Many people retake or have a gap year and attend the following year.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Consider other options</strong> ? university is not for everyone. There are other options available that will still allow you to start your dream career and get to where you want to be.</li>\n 	<li><strong>Apply for a BTEC course</strong> - sometimes these courses have lower acceptance grades and may be an option for you o</li>\n</ul>\nIf your results are better than expected?\n\n<strong>CONGRATULATIONS!</strong> All that hard work has paid off! If you are planning to go to university, check UCAS Track. This will have confirmation of your place and the instructions on how to confirm.\n\nHowever, you can also choose to apply through Adjustment and see if there are any places in other university or on different courses that these higher grades will allow you to apply to.\n<h2><strong>After Results Day</strong></h2>\n<h3>Enjoy yourself!</h3>\nAll the stress of results day isover and you can look forward to what is to come. Make the most of your summer and be proud of what you have achieved.\n\nIf you need any more help with choosing what to do after results day, our student adviser team are more than happy to help. Call us on <strong>03300 563 100</strong> and we can take the stress out of results day.',NULL,NULL,9,'2018-08-22 10:56:34','2018-08-22 10:56:34',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/8755-autosave-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(1942,'What\'s Next? Other Options Post GCSEs','options-post-gcses',NULL,NULL,'It?s the day after.\n\nYou?ve received your GCSE results, good or bad, and now you?re planning your future. But who says that future needs to be the path that is pre-set for you?\n\nWhen we?re at school, we get told to do GCSEs, do A Levels, go to university and be successful; that?s a great route. But it?s not the only route that you can take. After your GCSEs, there are other options that can get you to where you want to be and help you to become just as successful.\n\nThe law states that children under 18 must do one of the following:\n<ul>\n 	<li>?stay in full-time education</li>\n 	<li>start anapprenticeshiportraineeship</li>\n 	<li>spend 20 hours or more a week working or volunteering, while in part-time education or training?</li>\n</ul>\nSo your options are varied depending on what you want to do.\n<h3><strong>Resits</strong></h3>\nIf you didn?t quite get the grades that you wanted, you can always choose to redo your GCSEs to improve your chances of better grades. Our range of GCSEs and iGCSEs are nationally recognised and can be studied from home to allow you to study alongside any other commitments you may have.\n<h3><strong>A Levels</strong></h3>\nThe natural next step after GCSEs, A Levels are the most common choice for students. Whether you choose to study at a college or sixth form, or study from home with distance learning, you can gain the necessary knowledge and skills you need to progress onto university or future endeavours by studying A Levels.\n<h3><strong>Apprenticeships</strong></h3>\nApprenticeships are a great option for those who do not wish to continue into full-time education. This is suitable for those who know what career they wish to enter, as you can receive hands-on training and experience to kick-start your future.\n<h3><strong>Study while you work</strong></h3>\nDistance learning courses are perfect for allowing you to do a mix of activities. Perhaps you could take up some volunteer work to gain experience and meet new people. Or maybe you could get a full-time job to save money for university or any future plans.\n<h2><strong>Why Choose Open Study College?</strong></h2>\nOpen Study College is one of the UK?s leading distance learning providers with over 11 years? worth of experience in the industry. During this time, more 73,000 students have furthered their education and developed their career prospects by studying a course or qualification with us.\n\nWith a varied range of qualifications, this way of studying offers endless opportunities to all students.\n<ul>\n 	<li>Flexible &amp; Convenient</li>\n 	<li>Affordable Study</li>\n 	<li>Unlimited Tutor Support</li>\n 	<li>Student Perk</li>\n</ul>\nDon?t think you have to follow the same path that has been paved for you; you are more than capable of paving your own.\n\nIf you need any more information or help with choosing your options, call our student adviser team on03300 563 100who will be more than happy to help. Or head over to our <a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/pages/how-it-works.html\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>website</strong></span></a> to see all the qualifications and courses that can help your career.',NULL,NULL,9,'2018-08-24 15:20:54','2018-08-24 15:20:54',2,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/?p=8777',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
