	(2101,'3 reasons why a company hires a finance professional','9162-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'So you?re thinking of studying towards becoming a self-employed bookkeeper or accountant. First things first, is it worth it? Is there enough demand out there? What are the reasons why a company hires a finance professional, rather than looking after the numbers in house?\n\nThe good news is that even small companies hire finance professionals to look after their finances. This means there are plenty of potential clients out there, in all sorts of industries.\n\nHere are some of the reasons a company hires a finance professional\n<h1>To save money</h1>\nPaying to hire the services of a professional costs a business more money, surely? On the surface it would appear so. But a good accountant will be able to advise on where to cut costs or make changes to improve the figures. Anything spent on the expertise of a professional will be recouped in the positive savings they make for a business.\n<h1>To gain more time</h1>\nMost companies hire employees in a role in which they specialise ? be that sales, marketing, admin or something else. An employee who doesn?t specialise in bookkeeping but has been tasked with the job is therefore wasting time they could be spending on their actual role. A non-expert will invariably take much longer to complete a bookkeeping task than someone who is qualified and accredited. Most companies realise it?s best to trust the finances to the experts! This frees up their employees to do the jobs they?re employed for.\n<h1>To avoid breaking the law</h1>\nNo-one wants to get on the wrong side of the taxman. The consequences can be fatal for a small business and severely damaging for larger ones. Unpaid monies, fines and harm to reputation are all to be avoided; whatever the size of the organisation. When a company hires a finance professional they remove their fear of breaking the law, however unintentionally. This gives business owners peace of mind that their affairs are in good hands. Of course, as a highly qualified and accredited professional, you?ll have no such worries about getting things wrong, because you?ll have studied with Beancounters and received full tutor support for the duration of your course!\n\nReady to find out more about becoming a finance professional?\n\nBrowse our<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/bookkeeping-courses\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"color: #000032;\"> accounting, bookkeeping and payroll</span></a> courses, or<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">visit our website</a>for more information.\n\nPrefer to speak to someone? Call our team of student advisers on 03300 563100. They?re available Monday to Friday 9am to 9pm, and Saturdays from 12pm to 6pm.',NULL,NULL,9,'2019-04-24 14:50:11','2019-04-24 14:50:11',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/9162-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
	(2102,'5 celebrities who studied accounting','9165-revision-v1',NULL,NULL,'<h1>The road to becoming a celebrity doesn\'t always run smoothly</h1>\nMany famous people had a ?before? life that may not be so widely known. Being a rockstar, for example, is great if you can make it. But it?s always good to have a back up career in mind just in case!\n\nHere are 5 celebrities who studied accounting. ? would you have guessed any of them?\n<h2>Mick Jagger</h2>\nBefore one of the most famous and enduring bands on the planet was born, Mick Jagger was a student atthe London School of Economic, learning finance and accounting thanks to a scholarship place,\n\nThanks to his friendship with Keith Richards and Brian Jones, Jagger became more and more ensconced in the world of rock ?n? roll, and lasted less than a year at LSE before leaving to become a full time musician.\n<h2>Robert Plant</h2>\nAnother giant of the rock ?n? roll world was originally destined for a life of working with numbers. Plant?s Dad wanted him to become a chartered accountant, and enrolled him in lessons at the age of 16.\n\nUltimately his love of music won out, and he abandoned the lessons after just 2 weeks, in order to study music at college.\n<h2>John Grisham</h2>\nBefore famous legal thriller writer John Grisham became an author, he studied accounting at college; achieving his degree with the intention to progress onto study tax law. At law school he chose to study criminal law instead, which gave him lots of understanding and knowledge to apply to his books ? some of which would go on to be made into Hollywood movies.\n<h2>Eddie Izzard</h2>\nComedian Eddie Izzard comes from accounting stock ? his father was an accountant. Izzard went on to study the subject at the University of Sheffield, but failed all his exams and was unable to retake them.\n\nAccounting?s loss was comedy?s gain, as Izzard dedicated himself to performing.\n<h2>Kenny G</h2>\nJazz saxophonist Kenny G has sold more than 75 million records worldwide. Prior to becoming successful on a global scale, he graduated from the University of Washington with a degree in accounting. He credits his background with helping him to manage his finances during his early career, and also used his knowledge and experience when it came to employing an accountant as his career progressed.\n<h3>Now, we\'re not saying that studying accounting can turn you into a celebrity!</h3>\nBut it will enable you to pursuea future-proof careerwhich is in demand in every type of industry across the world.\n\n<a href=\"https://www.openstudycollege.com/bookkeeping-courses\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">View our full range of accounting courses</a>.\n\nPrefer to speak to someone about the courses we offer? Call us on 03300 563100.\n\n&nbsp;',NULL,NULL,9,'2019-04-24 15:15:57','2019-04-24 15:15:57',1,'https://blog.openstudycollege.com/9165-revision-v1/',1,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL),
